Zhang Guangjun was appointed vice governor of Guangdong Province.
The fifth meeting of the Standing Committee of the 13th National People's Congress of Guangdong Province held its second plenary meeting in Guangzhou on the 30th.
After a vote, the meeting decided to appoint Zhang Guangjun as deputy governor of Guangdong Provincial People's Government.
Previously, Zhang Guangjun was the Deputy Secretary of the Party Committee of the Chinese Academy of Engineering Physics.
Resume of Comrade Zhang Guangjun: Zhang Guangjun, male, Han nationality, born in February 1968, born in Chongqing, joined the Party in April 1994, joined the work in July 1991, graduated from the Department of Radio Engineering, Harbin Institute of Technology, majored in electronic instruments and measurement technology, graduated from university, senior engineer, and enjoyed special allowance from the State Council.
He is currently the Vice Governor of the Guangdong Provincial Government and a member of the Party Group.
1987-1991 Major in Electronic Instrumentation and Measurement Technology, Department of Radio Engineering, Harbin Institute of Technology
1991-1998 Technician, Deputy Director, Secretary and Deputy Director of the General Engineering Research Institute of the Chinese Academy of Engineering Physics
1998-2002 Deputy Director of the General Engineering Research Institute of the Chinese Academy of Engineering Physics and Deputy Secretary of the Party Committee (meanwhile: 1999.05-2000.12 also served as the Secretary of the Commission of Discipline of the Institute, 2001.09-2001.12 Sichuan Provincial Party School and Office-level Cadres Refresher Course)
From 2002 to 2002, the party secretary and deputy director of the General Engineering Research Institute of the Chinese Academy of Engineering Physics (inter alia: 2002.03-2004.05)
2002 - 2009 Director of the Political Department of the Chinese Academy of Engineering and Physics, Director of the Office of the Party Committee, Vice President of the Party School (during: 2005.09 - 2006.01 Training Course for Young Cadres of the Central Party School)
2009-2014 Director of the Major Special Management Office of the Chinese Academy of Engineering and Physics (during which: 2011.09 - 2012.01 Central Party School training course for young and middle-aged cadres)
2014-2015 Assistant to the President of the Chinese Academy of Engineering Physics and Director of the Office of Major Engineering Management
2015-2018 Deputy Secretary of the Party Committee of the Chinese Academy of Engineering and Physics
In September 2018, he was Vice Governor of the Guangdong Provincial Government and a member of the Party Group.
According to British media, U.S. Vice Admiral William Moran said that even as the U.S. Navy is re-energizing to deal with an increasingly worrisome Russia on both sides of the Atlantic, the U.S. continues to make the Asia-Pacific region - which the Pentagon has expanded to include the Indo-Asia-Pacific - the focus of the Navy.
According to a report on the website of Britain's Jane's Defence Weekly on September 24, the United States listed China and Russia as strategic competitors in the new national defense strategy published at the beginning of the year.
Since then, the U.S. Navy has restored the Second Fleet in order to confront Russian activities more directly.
According to the report, these moves have raised some questions and concerns among allies and analysts, who fear that the US Navy may move away from the "Asia-Pacific rebalancing" strategy that marked the Obama administration.
But Admiral Moran says the focus of the U.S. Navy remains the Western Pacific.
"There have been no major changes for us," he said on January 24, 2018, at a roundtable discussion entitled "Meeting the High Seas Challenge" hosted by the US National Bureau of Asian Studies in Washington.
"The focus is still on rebalancing, the shift of focus or whatever you want to describe it," Moran said.
He acknowledged, however, that the United States has close relations with Europe.
"We will continue to focus on the growth of the West Coast and balance what we can do," he said.
While Moran pointed out that the overall policy on Russia falls within the purview of the US Secretary of Defense, he warned: "The Russians may face demographic and economic challenges, but history has proven that if we clash with them, they will be very tough."
Admiral Moran said the U.S. Navy is dynamically deploying its troops into a "new mode of operations" as part of a renewed U.S. operation against Russia, China and other competitors, which will help to catch rivals off guard as to where U.S. aircraft carrier groups or other assets will be deployed at any given time and place.
"We in the Navy and Marine Corps support it - the concept of operational unpredictability, don't be in the same place again and again, almost like clockwork - it's our approach," he said.
According to the report, the first to try this new approach was the "Harry Truman" aircraft carrier battle group, whose early deployment included working visits to the port and patrolling in areas that are usually only passed through.
Moran said the U.S. Navy is now working to ensure allies know that the ships will still patrol the traditional areas, and is also addressing logistical and family liaison issues for the new deployment procedures.
The head of the Royal Australian Navy, Lieutenant General Michael Noonan, also spoke at the event, saying that the Australian military could work seamlessly with the US aircraft carrier strike group.
He said the situation will continue as the Royal Australian Navy plans to procure nine more frigates equipped with Aegis combat systems.
From October 5, a number of airlines have raised or restored fuel surcharges. From next Friday, aircraft travel will be more expensive
Yesterday, Xiangpeng Airlines, Okai Airlines and other airlines announced that, with effect from October 5, 2018 (the date of issue), the fuel surcharge for domestic routes will be RMB20 per passenger on routes up to 800 km (including) and RMB30 per passenger on routes over 800 km.
Xiangpeng Airlines, Okai Airlines and other companies announced that from October 5, 2018, at the zero point (date of issue), the fuel surcharge rate for domestic routes under 800 km (including) will be increased from RMB10 per person to RMB20 per person, and the fuel surcharge rate for domestic routes over 800 km will be increased from RMB10 per person to RMB30 per person.
Children and military police are all 10 yuan per person. Infants continue to be exempted from collection.
According to the person in charge of the Ctrip ticket, the airline has indicated in the notice that the fuel surcharge will be charged according to the original date of issue. When the passenger ticket is exchanged, the fuel surcharge will not be refunded.
This means that domestic airline tickets issued before October 5 will not have to pay the fuel surcharge according to the new standard if they are to be changed to October 5 (inclusive).
Since June 5, 2018, a number of airlines, including Air China, Eastern Airlines, HNA, Shanghai Airlines, Spring and Autumn Airlines, Shenzhen Airlines, Western Airlines and Okai Airlines, have resumed charging domestic fuel surcharges, which have been cancelled for three years, with a standard of 10 yuan per person.
This time, Xiangpeng Airlines and Okai Airlines took the lead in announcing the increase of fuel surcharge. As of the press release, they have not seen the news of the follow-up adjustment announced by the four major domestic airlines.
It is also understood that the Hong Kong Civil Aviation Department has stipulated that airlines can decide whether to charge fuel surcharges on their own from November.
Cathay Pacific announced at the earliest on September 27 that it would re-charge the fuel surcharge from November 2.
According to the Cathay Pacific website, all tickets issued or re-issued by Cathay Pacific and Cathay Dragon on or after November 2 will include a fuel surcharge of $652 for long-haul flights to and from Hong Kong and the South-West Pacific, North America, Europe, the Middle East and India, and Africa, and $146 for short-haul flights.
The fee is applicable to all ticket types, calculated according to each flight segment, and includes the ticket price of all direct sales channels in Cathay.
On the eve of the 69th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China, Chinese Premier Li Keqiang met with the new ambassadors of 29 countries and regions to China at the Great Hall of the People on the afternoon of the 30th.
Li Keqiang shook hands and talked cordially with all the envoys in China.
Li Keqiang welcomed the envoys to take up their new duties in China, and asked them to convey sincere greetings and good wishes to the leaders and people of all relevant countries and leaders of relevant institutions.
Li Keqiang made positive comments on China's good relations with other countries and regions. He stressed that China is committed to enhancing bilateral political mutual trust, deepening pragmatic cooperation, and strengthening coordination and cooperation in international and regional affairs. He hoped that the ambassadors will walk around and see more, and make new positive contributions to promoting the development of China's relations with their respective countries and regions in their new posts.
The Chinese government is willing to provide convenience and support to enable the envoys to perform their duties.
Li Keqiang pointed out that China adheres to the path of peaceful development and unswervingly promotes economic globalization.
This year marks the 40th anniversary of China's reform and opening up. As the largest developing country in the world, we are willing to achieve common development with all countries in the further expansion of opening up.
Against the backdrop of rising protectionism and unilateralism, we are willing to work with all parties to continue to consolidate and strengthen the partnership on the basis of the principles of mutual respect, equality and mutual benefit, promote the docking development strategy, promote the "Belt and Road" construction cooperation on the basis of the principle of common consultation, building and sharing, work together to safeguard multilateralism and free trade, build an open world economy, and inject new impetus into promoting the stable and balanced development of the world economy.
The ambassadors of various countries and institutions in China warmly congratulated the 69th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China, conveyed the greetings of the leaders of their respective countries and institutions to the Chinese leaders and people, and said that China has made outstanding achievements in its development and believes that further deepening reform and opening up in the future will bring more development opportunities to the world.
They are willing to play a positive role in promoting the friendly cooperation between their respective countries and regions and China and better achieving mutual benefit and win-win results.
Subsequently, envoys of various countries and institutions in China attended the National Day reception at the invitation of Li Keqiang.
State Councilor and Minister of Foreign Affairs Wang Yi attended the event.
Japan's Itochu Commercial on Friday recognized a $1.3 billion impairment loss on its investment in China's CITIC shares, taking a writedown on its largest corporate investment deal because of the impact of trade tensions between China and the United States.
In May 2016, in Tokyo, Japan, a man walked past the headquarters of Maru Hong Corporation.
Maru Hong said that the trade war hit its U.S. grain division, Gao Hong, and that it had suspended financial transactions in agriculture.
Some Japanese heavy equipment manufacturers, telecommunications companies and others have warned of the impact of Sino-U.S. trade frictions when they released their latest results, and now these Japanese trading houses have also joined the ranks.
The United States and China have imposed tariffs on hundreds of billions of dollars of each other's goods. U.S. President Donald Trump has threatened to extend the levy to all over $500 billion of Chinese goods exported to the United States if the dispute cannot be resolved.
The impact of trade disputes on China's economy is likely to be greater next year, according to Tsuyoshi Hachimura, Itochu's commercial finance chief.
Itochu Commercial and Thailand's Boho Group invested $10 billion in CITIC in 2015, acquiring a 20% stake in it.
According to Hachimura, Itozhong Commercial filed a 143.3 billion yen (US $1.3 billion) loss on the stake because it believed that Citic shares would not recover in the near future.
Itochu maintains its profit forecast for the fiscal year ending March 31, 2019 at 500 billion yen.
China imposed a 25% import tariff on U.S. soybeans in July to counter Washington's move in trade frictions.
"Our cereal business has been hit by U.S.-China trade frictions," said Yanhong Yabe, Maru Hong's finance chief.
He said that Gao Hong has stopped financial transactions in his own account since September.
Gaohong spokesman Pat Burke said in a statement Friday that the company's move was "subject to internal policy restrictions and due to lack of market opportunities."
He also said that the suspension of financial transactions will not lead to the loss of jobs.
Maru Hong maintained its annual profit forecast of 230 billion yen unchanged, helped by pulp and paper and power generation business.
Sumitomo on Thursday reported a 16% increase in profits between April and September, stressing that "the future is uncertain due to the trade issues between the United States and China."
Mitsubishi raised its annual profit forecast to a record level on Friday, attributed to higher coking coal production and higher prices for commodities such as oil and coal.
Mitsubishi also announced a new business plan, aiming to increase its profit to 900 billion yen (US $7.98 billion) in the fiscal year ending March 31, 2022, from 640 billion yen estimated this year.
