People's Network Beijing, November 5 (Wang Xiaoyan) Under the current wave of "mass entrepreneurship, mass innovation ", more and more technology companies are beginning to attach importance to patent research and development and related protection work, dig deep into the potential value of patents, and occupy market dominance.
Similarly, there are also a number of technology enterprises in patent technology licensing, the use of patented technology and other aspects have encountered a significant wave of infringement.
At the end of 2017, three people from Guangdong Province, Tan Wei, He Zhanghong and Lai Bin, on the grounds of patent infringement, filed a lawsuit against the Guangzhou Intellectual Property Court against the developer of "Drop Trip" APP, Beijing Small Orange Technology Co., Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as Little Orange Technology), the operator Drop Trip Technology Co., Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as Drop Trip), and the seller, Guangdong Pacific Internet Information Service Co., Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as Guangdong Pacific).
The three plaintiffs requested a court order, and the three defendants immediately stopped manufacturing, selling, promising to sell, and using the plaintiff's patent.
On October 30, 2018, the China Judicial Documents Network published "the first-instance civil ruling of the dispute between Tan Wei, He Zhanghong and Beijing Xiaoqiang Technology Co., Ltd. on infringement of patent rights for inventions ", disclosing the details of some of the cases in which DDT travel APP was sued for patent infringement.
The three plaintiffs believe that the patent holder and inventor of the patent for “carpooling service system and method based on mobile terminals ”, and that the entire operation process of“ ride-hailing ” application in “Drop Trip ” APP corresponds to the technical scheme of patent protection involved in the case, constituting patent infringement.
However, during the court ruling, Xiao Orange Science and Technology held that Guangdong Pacific was not a suitable defendant. It only provided free downloads of the APP "drip travel" involved in the case on the Internet. It did not implement the patent method involved. There was no direct or indirect infringement and should not be listed as a defendant in the case.
Secondly, the place of tort in this case is not in Guangdong.
According to the law, the place of infringement of the patent involved should be the place for the complete implementation of the patent method involved. Therefore, the jurisdiction of the court was challenged, and the case was requested to be transferred to the court of the defendant's place of residence, namely, the Beijing Intellectual Property Court.
The Guangzhou Intellectual Property Court held that the defendant, Guangdong Pacific, provided the alleged infringing DDT travel APP products on its online platform, and that it was not inappropriate for the plaintiff to list the defendant, Guangdong Pacific, as the defendant.
And the defendant's Guangdong Pacific domicile is located in Guangzhou, which is under the jurisdiction of the Guangzhou Intellectual Property Court.
The defendant, Xiao Orange Science and Technology, argued that the case should be transferred to the Beijing Intellectual Property Court for trial. On the basis of insufficient evidence, the defendant, Xiao Orange Science and Technology Co., Ltd., rejected the objection to the jurisdiction of the case, and bear the expenses for accepting the case of jurisdiction objection.
At present, the other trials of the case have not been announced. Journalists will also pay close attention to the follow-up details of the patent infringement case of DDT travel.
Interview with the Chief Executive Officer of the Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organization of Australia: Remarkable achievements in Australia-China scientific and technological cooperation
"China's science and technology has developed rapidly in the past few decades. Australia and China can achieve fruitful results by working together in the field of science."
Larry Marshall, chief executive of the Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organization of Australia, said in a recent interview with the China News Agency in Beijing that the cooperation between Australia and China in the field of science and technology, from the fight against climate change to the cooperation of the "Eye in the Sky" project, has shown great vitality.
As the largest national scientific research institution in the Commonwealth of Australia, CSIRO has achieved many innovative research results in the fields of ocean, energy, biology, materials, astronomy and other fields that have attracted worldwide attention.
CSIRO has always maintained close cooperation with scientific research institutions such as the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
"This is a lasting friendship that embraces trust in partners and a tradition of long-term cooperation," Marshall said.
In May this year, China's 500-meter-caliber spherical radio telescope, the "China SkyEye ", installed the first 19-beam L-band receiver in the world.
This 19-beam feeder receiver, currently the most advanced in the world, is jointly developed by Chinese and Australian scientists.
Marshall said that the successful development of the receiver is based on the accumulated technology of CSIRO for many years. After the launch, the speed of the FAST survey will be increased by five to six times. At the same time, more scientific observation targets will be expanded.
"It's a contribution of CSIRO to FAST."
In addition to the above-mentioned cooperation, CSIRO also has close cooperation with Chinese scientific research institutions in the construction of a square kilometer array radio telescope, the development of new fuel technologies, energy conservation and emission reduction.
"In the past, scientific research has tended to focus on the problems of the past 100 years, and now more scientific research is needed to solve the problems in front of us."
Marshall believes that Australia and China are complementary in the field of scientific development, while both countries face a series of challenges in their development.
For example, extreme weather frequently occurs around the world. Droughts and floods have led to a reduction in food production. Food shortages have seriously affected the development of mankind.
At the same time, the population explosion, aging, chronic diseases and other issues are also serious challenges currently faced.
"The cooperation between Australia and China in recent years is mainly focused on solving these current problems."
Marshall said that the work of the International Southern Hemisphere Ocean Research Center, jointly established by CSIRO and the Qingdao National Laboratory of Marine Science and Technology, is focused on observing the El Niño and La Niña phenomena, studying the relationship between the two and extreme weather, and establishing early warning facilities for extreme weather. The new grain varieties developed by CSIRO and the Chinese Academy of Sciences to overcome extreme weather can also alleviate the food shortage caused by extreme weather.
"In the current environment, scientific and technological innovation is difficult to accomplish on its own, requires extremely high costs, and there are many problems to be solved. Therefore, cooperation is particularly important in today's world."
Marshall said that the closer the cooperation, the more likely it will be to make breakthrough progress. This is also the significance of strengthening cooperation between Australia and China under the framework of "Belt and Road ".
"To strengthen bilateral cooperation, it is mainly cooperation in science and technology for us."
Marshall said, for example, that CSIRO has recently developed a gold purification method that does not use cyanide. Because the traditional cyanide gold purification method is very harmful to the environment, many countries hope to find a gold purification method with little environmental pollution.
"We are very willing to introduce this technology to China, which is one of the results of our participation in the" Belt and Road "cooperation."
