Active treatment, the survival rate of preterm infants aged 29 weeks and above in China reached 98%, which has reached the level of developed countries.
On September 30, CNN Shanghai (Chen Jing Luo Yanqian) National Children's Medical Center and Fudan University Affiliated Paediatric Hospital disclosed that it had introduced Canada's advanced method in the leading "Project for Improving the Prognosis Quality of Premature Infants in China NICU Hospital ".
The results of the project showed that after active treatment, the survival rate of preterm infants aged 29 weeks and above in China reached 98%, which has reached the level of developed countries. However, there is still much room for improvement in the survival rate of preterm infants with minimal gestational age and preterm infants without complications.
For the past 20 years, the Chinese government has been concerned about the treatment of newborn babies.
At present, the infant mortality rate in the Shanghai area has fallen to 3.71 per thousand, significantly lower than the national average and reaching the advanced level of developed countries.
"The Project for Improving the Prognosis Quality of Premature Infants in Hospitalized NICU in China" has significantly improved the quality of life of premature babies through four years of unremitting efforts.
Professor Cao Yun, director of the Neonatal Intensive Care Unit (NICU) of the Paediatric Hospital affiliated to Fudan University, told reporters that while improving the survival rate of preterm infants, attention should be paid to reducing the quality of survival of preterm infants, reducing the incidence of complications, improving the prognosis of neurodevelopment and improving the overall outcome of children. This is of great significance for improving the overall quality of life and the quality of the population of preterm infants. It is an important issue of concern to the pediatric and neonatal community at home and abroad. It is also a key issue of concern for this project.
Through four years of unremitting efforts, the "Project for Improving the Quality of Prognosis of Premature Infants in Hospitalized NICU in China" included tens of thousands of premature babies with gestational age of 33 weeks and below. This resulted in a one-third reduction in the mortality rate of premature infants with small gestational age and small birth weight. At the same time, the incidence of serious complications of premature infants decreased significantly, greatly improving the quality of life of premature infants.
Through the establishment of a national cooperative network for improving the quality of newborns, and the introduction of the concept of collaborative quality improvement, the project radiates 25 cooperative hospitals across China, and establishes a set of integrated, systematic and effective methods for improving the quality of collaboration for improving the prognosis of premature infants and improving the level of newborn care.
The Paediatric Hospital affiliated to Fudan University is working with the National Neonatal Unit to draw up guidelines for the diagnosis and treatment of neonatal infections based on the accumulated experience of the project, so as to provide reference and guidance for the standard diagnosis and treatment of neonatal infections in China.
It is understood that in the "Prognosis Quality Improvement Project for Premature Infants in China ", the pediatric hospital introduced the EPIQ method to 25 large-scale NICUs in 19 provinces across the country. It is committed to solving the problem of premature infant infection that plagues the neonatal care unit in China.
After more than 10 years of continuous improvement, the complication-free survival rate of premature babies in Canada has increased by about one-third. Canada is now one of the countries with the best prognosis for premature babies in the world.
The EPIQ method has now been applied to all NICUs in Canada, and has been adopted and applied in six countries.
The paediatric hospital revealed that the results of the study showed that two years after the EPIQ intervention, the infection of premature babies fell by 35%, while the use of antibiotics fell by 20%.
In the future, the Paediatric Hospital affiliated to Fudan University will continue to popularize and implement this method to the whole country, with a view to comprehensively reducing the incidence of all complications of premature babies and improving the quality of treatment for newborns throughout the country.
At present, it is an indisputable fact that there are differences and heterogeneity in the level of treatment in various regions of China.
According to Professor Cao Yun, as an important construction unit of the National Children's Medical Center, pediatric hospitals will play a leading role in radiation. This study covers a number of western provinces, including Xinjiang, Guizhou, Gansu and Shaanxi, with a view to gradually promoting the homogenization and standardization of newborn care throughout the country.
It is understood that the Paediatric Hospital affiliated to Fudan University is working with the National Neonatal Unit to draw up guidelines for the diagnosis and treatment of neonatal infections based on the accumulated experience of the project, so as to provide reference and guidance for the standard diagnosis and treatment of neonatal infections in China.
It was revealed that in 2019, the China Neonatal Collaboration Network, located at the Paediatric Hospital affiliated to Fudan University, will work with 63 hospitals across the country to carry out the next phase of national quality improvement, with a view to promoting the balanced development of the level of newborn care in China.
Wu Jinglei, director of the Shanghai Municipal Health and Family Planning Commission, said that Shanghai can become a central city in the heart of Asia, not only in research, but also in the construction of the entire service system. The quality of services and the results of services should have a place in Asia, thus truly reflecting China's medical level.
