BRUSSELS, Sept 28 (Reuters) - The European Union took a non-confrontational stance against Italy on Friday after Italy defied EU demands and surprised markets with a massive budget deficit plan, but the EU may take a more aggressive stance if Italy sticks to too bold a goal.
Italy ’ s Euroskeptic government is targeting a budget deficit equivalent to 2.4% of gross domestic product (GDP) for the next three years, suggesting that there is still no debt reduction in the face of deficit reduction requirements.
"We have no interest in the crisis between the Commission and Italy," the European Commission's economic affairs executive, Moscovici, said on Friday, taking a cautious response as the EU's proposals and sanctions may have little impact on Italy.
EU officials and diplomats still hope that market forces will be able to persuade Italy to adjust its budget plan before it is formally presented to the European Commission in mid-October.
The euro fell to its lowest level in nearly two weeks on Friday after the government announced its plans, while Italian bond yields hit their highest in three weeks.
If the deficit target remains unchanged by the October deadline, the European Commission may veto Italy's draft budget, something it has never done to any country.
At a meeting in the Latvian capital Riga later on Friday, the vice president of the European Commission said Italy's current fiscal plan "does not seem to be in line with the Stability and Growth Pact," referring to the EU's fiscal rules.
But he did not say how that would trigger a reaction from the EU.
