Xinhua News Agency, Fuzhou, October 1, by wire (reporter Tai Xiao'an) October 1, the "Regulations on the Safety Management of Fujian Province High-speed Railway" was officially implemented.
According to the regulations, it is forbidden to fly kites, balloons, Kongming lamps, aircraft and other airborne objects and small aircraft within 500 meters of each side of the high-speed rail power line.
It stipulates that on the basis of the Railway Law of the People's Republic of China, the Regulations on the Administration of Railway Safety and other higher-ranking laws, and in accordance with the geographical and climatic characteristics of Fujian Province, supplementary provisions shall be made on the prohibited and restricted acts that affect the safety of high-speed rail, regulate construction and tree planting along the high-speed rail line, further clarify the subject of high-speed rail supervision and the scope of supervision, and clarify the duties and legal responsibilities of law enforcement supervision.
In view of the high winds along the coast of Fujian Province, the light construction (construction) materials and light drifts along the high-speed rail line are blown into the high-speed rail to affect safety. It is stipulated that flying kites, balloons, Kongming lamps, power umbrellas, aircraft and other airborne objects and small aircraft are prohibited within 500 meters of each side of the high-speed rail power line.
In addition, the owners or users of light objects such as plastic sheds, colored steel plates and sunshade nets along the high-speed rail line, as well as low-altitude floating objects and plastic protective films produced during the construction process, shall take reinforcing and protective measures to prevent endangering the safety of high-speed railway.
In view of the fact that Fujian Province is located in a hilly area and has a large number of high-speed railway tunnels, it is stipulated that within 200 meters of each side of the central line above the high-speed railway tunnel, the construction of mountain ponds, reservoirs, dykes, the excavation of river channels, trunk channels, and the drilling of wells, which may affect the safety of the tunnel, should seek the opinions of the railway construction unit or the railway transport enterprise.
At the same time, those responsible for violating the Provisions will be ordered by the public security organs to make corrections; if the circumstances are serious, the unit shall be fined not less than 5,000 yuan but not more than 10,000 yuan, and the individual shall be fined not less than 200 yuan but not more than 500 yuan; if the circumstances are serious, the unit shall also be fined not less than 10,000 yuan but not more than 30,000 yuan, and the individual shall be fined not less than 500 yuan but not more than 1,000 yuan.
Those who have caused losses shall be liable for compensation in accordance with the law.
It is understood that with the rapid development of railway construction, the high-speed railway mileage of 200 km/h and above in Fujian Province has now reached 1,516 km/h, and has achieved city-to-city mobility. It is expected that the railway line of 200 km/h and above in Fujian Province will reach 2,150 km/h in the next five years.
The implementation of this regulation will standardize the safety management of high-speed rail in Fujian Province, further implement the responsibilities of local government departments, coordinate the railway and local forces, work together to ensure the safety of high-speed rail, and improve the prevention and control system of high-speed rail safety in Fujian Province.
HONG KONG, Nov 5 (Reuters) - China Resources Beer (Holdings) Co Ltd (0291.HK), the country's largest beer producer, announced on Monday the acquisition of six breweries set up in the mainland by Heineken/Heinigan (HEIN.AS) through its China Resources Snow Brewery, as well as the total issued share capital of Heineken Hong Kong, at a total cost of about HK $2,355 million.
At the same time, the company also signed a trademark licensing agreement with Heineken, authorizing China Resources Snow to use the relevant Heineken® trademark to produce, market, distribute and sell licensed products in mainland China, Hong Kong and Macau for a period of 20 years. Thereafter, it will be renewed under the same terms and conditions for a period of 10 years at a time, until the termination clause of the trademark license agreement is terminated.
China Resources Beer announced in August this year that its direct controlling shareholder, China Resources Group (Beer) Co., Ltd., and Heineken have reached an equity cooperation agreement involving up to HK $28.5 billion.
At the same time, China Resources Beer and Heineken have reached a long-term strategic cooperation arrangement, which includes the acquisition of Heineken's existing business in China, Hong Kong and Macau, and the integration with China Resources Beer's beer business within China.
This transaction is the further implementation of the cooperation agreement.
China Resources Beer said that the transaction with Heineken provides the Group with an important strategy to expand into the high-end beer market, long-term development and value enhancement opportunities. The long-term cooperative relationship established between the two sides will be highly complementary.
China Resources Beer closed at HK $28.85 on Friday, down nearly 4.5% over the past month.
The number of people killed or as many as thousands in the aftermath of Indonesia's powerful earthquake and tsunami - CNN
According to a comprehensive report, a 7.5-magnitude shallow earthquake hit the Indonesian island of Sulawesi on September 28, triggering a 6-meter-high tsunami.
The national disaster response department announced on September 30 that the death toll rose to 832, mainly concentrated in Palu, the capital, and Dungara County, near the epicenter.
Vice President Kara pointed out that as the number of casualties in some of the affected areas has still not been calculated, the number of victims may be as many as thousands.
A powerful earthquake and tsunami in Indonesia's Central Sulawesi province on the afternoon of September 28 have killed 832 people.
2.4 million people affected by the collapse of thousands of buildings
Palu was devastated after the disaster. Thousands of buildings collapsed and several roads were broken. Authorities said about 2.4 million people were estimated to have been affected.
A hotel on the local coast collapsed and only 24 guests escaped safely. An estimated 50 to 60 people were trapped in the rubble pile. From time to time, cries for help were heard at the scene. Rescue workers successfully rescued a young woman on September 30.
In order to ensure the safety of those trapped, the authorities were unable to use heavy machinery to remove the rubble, and the search and rescue process was slow.
A shopping mall in the city also collapsed. Hundreds of residents arrived at the scene, waiting for news from relatives and friends.
Many residents have used social platforms to send messages in search of lost friends and relatives.
On September 30, local time, a hotel collapsed in the city of Baru, Central Sulawesi, Indonesia, and rescue work began.
The whereabouts of 5 foreigners are unknown in Palu, where 10,000 people are to be rescued
Authorities say about 10,000 people are waiting to be rescued in the city of Palu, scattered across 50 locations.
It is reported that 71 foreigners were in Palu at the time of the earthquake. For the time being, 66 of them are known to be safe, including 21 Chinese citizens. The whereabouts of the remaining 2 French, 2 Malaysian tourists and 1 South Korean are unknown.
The Chinese Embassy in Indonesia is working through various channels to understand and verify the situation of Chinese citizens in the disaster area. No reports of casualties among Chinese citizens have been received for the time being.
Communications in Dungara County, near the epicenter of the quake, were still suspended, and 11 people were temporarily killed, but no further details were available.
According to the scene footage, the coastal area and port of Dungara County were severely damaged. A large number of buildings were swept away and bodies were scattered everywhere. Red Cross rescue teams were on their way to the local search and rescue.
Indonesia's president inspects the disaster and says reconstruction work will begin as soon as possible
Roads in Palu and Dungara were severely damaged. On September 30, Palu Airport was only open for use by aircraft carrying relief supplies, allowing relief supplies and personnel to arrive as soon as possible and remove the seriously injured.
A number of local hospitals are still without power, and the injured have to be treated outdoors.
More than 10,000 people were admitted to the reception center. Some people were afraid of aftershocks and preferred to spend the night in the open air.
Following the collapse of a prison in Palu during the earthquake, which triggered the escape of hundreds of prisoners, more than 100 prisoners in Dungara County also took advantage of the chaos caused by the earthquake, and prisoners set fire to riot in the detention center.
Indonesian President Joko visited Palu on September 30 to inspect the disaster. He pointed out that it is very difficult to solve a large number of problems in a short period of time, including the resumption of communication.
He called on the victims to be patient and said the authorities would start the reconstruction work as soon as possible.
On the other hand, Indonesia's finance minister announced that the government has allocated 560 billion Indonesian rupiah for disaster relief.
A human case of H5N6 avian influenza has been confirmed in Guangdong Province
The Health Bureau said that according to the latest notification from the Mainland health department, a human case of H5N6 avian influenza was confirmed in Guangdong Province.
The Health Bureau urged residents to avoid contact with birds and pay attention to personal and food hygiene.
According to the data, the patient, a 22-year-old male, is now living in Baiyun District, Guangzhou City, Guangdong Province. He developed fever and other symptoms on September 25. He was admitted to hospital on September 26. He is currently being treated in isolation in hospital. His condition is critical.
The patient had slaughtered and eaten live poultry before the onset of the disease.
Since April 2014, there have been confirmed cases of H5N6 avian influenza in Sichuan, Guangdong, Yunnan, Hubei, Hunan, Anhui and Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
The Health Bureau will continue to maintain close contact with the health departments of the country and neighboring regions and the World Health Organization, and closely monitor the epidemic situation in various places and in Australia.
In order to prevent human infection with avian influenza, the Health Bureau urges the public to pay attention to the following:
Avoid contact with birds or their secretions and excreta. Wash hands immediately if in contact with them;
Do not buy or carry birds that have not been quarantined;
Do not eat poultry meat, offal, blood products and eggs that have not been thoroughly cooked;
pay attention to personal hygiene and wash hands frequently;
If you have fever, cough, breathing difficulties and other symptoms, you should wear a mask, seek medical treatment as soon as possible, and give details of travel history and animal contact history to your doctor.
