The new U.S.-Mexico-Canadian trade deal will retain U.S. President Donald Trump's ability to implement the threat of a 25 percent tariff on imported cars, while essentially exempting passenger cars, pickup trucks and auto parts imported from Canada and Mexico from paying tariffs, according to a subsidiary arrangement of the trade deal released Monday.
If Trump imposes so-called “Chapter 232 ” tariffs on cars for national security reasons, both Mexico and Canada will have a quota of 2.6 million tax-exempt passenger vehicles exported to the US each year.
Under the subsidiary arrangement, pickup trucks produced in the two countries will be fully exempted from the tariff.
If Trump imposes auto tariffs, Mexico will get a tax exemption quota of $108 billion per year for auto parts, and Canada will get a quota of $32.4 billion.
Both quotas are well above the current production levels of the two countries and provide room for growth of the two countries' exports.
WASHINGTON/Mexico, Sept 28 (Reuters) - After days of debate, U.S. President Donald Trump's administration and Canada are making concrete efforts to resolve their trade policy differences, Mexico said on Friday, raising hopes that the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) is expected to remain in the form of a trilateral agreement.
Despite the lack of details, the apparent progress was enough to prompt the governments of Mexico and the United States to abruptly halt plans to release the text of the two trade agreements and give Canada more time to join the agreement.
Mexican President-designate Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador told reporters in Mexico that the U.S. government has made new counter-proposals to the Canadian government and said he will continue to press for the participation of all three countries in NAFTA.
Mexican Economy Minister Ildefonso Guajardo said the time to submit the text of the U.S.-Mexico trade agreement to Mexican and U.S. legislation was delayed because the Canadian and U.S. governments tried to reach an agreement "very seriously."
"In the next 48 hours, we will know whether we have reached a text of a three-way agreement or have to publish the text of a two-way agreement," Guajardo said.
Guajardo said his U.S. and Canadian counterparts "specifically requested" that the release of the text be delayed.
A spokesman for the U.S. Trade Representative's Office (USTR) did not comment on the text of the U.S.-Mexican trade agreement and the U.S.-Canada consultations.
Officials from the Canadian Prime Minister's Office and the Foreign Minister's Office did not respond to requests for comment on the counter-proposal.
It's hard to see anything out of the ordinary at a conservation centre on the outskirts of Pretoria, South Africa's capital, where two young lions frolic and play together, but there's nothing unusual about them.
The University of Pretoria announced: "This is the first time that a young lion has ever been born by artificial insemination - the first pair in the world."
Scientists at the school are working on the reproductive system of the female African lion.
Gans Winter, director of the Institute of Mammal Studies at the University of Pretoria, said the two cubs, born on August 25, were a female and a male, quite healthy and normal.
After 18 months of intensive testing, his team finally reached the breakthrough.
"We collected sperm from a healthy male lion," Ganswinter said during a media visit.
Next, the researchers waited for the lioness to be artificially inseminated when the hormone levels in her body reached the right level.
"Fortunately, the result was successful," Ganswinter said.
He said the researchers "tried several times, but unexpectedly didn't put much effort into it."
He said that the aforementioned research breakthrough can be verified repeatedly, and scientists hope to use this technology to save the endangered big cats.
According to the International Union for Conservation of Nature, lions have become extinct in 26 countries in Africa, and the total number of surviving wild lions has plummeted by 43% in the past 20 years, leaving only about 20,000.
The African lion is classified as vulnerable by the organization.
"If we don't do something for this animal, they're going to face extinction," Gans Winter said.
He said the new technique does not require the lion to be raised, but simply injects sperm into a fertile lioness, just as North America and Europe have done with captive elephants.
