After being signed and approved by Premier Li Keqiang, the State Council has recently issued the Decision on Further Reducing the Catalogue of Industrial Products Production Licenses and Simplifying the Approval Procedure.
The Decision proposes to further reduce the list of industrial product production licenses, abolish the administration of production licenses for 14 categories of industrial products, and delegate the authority for the administration of production licenses for 4 categories of industrial products to the quality and technical supervision departments of provincial people's governments.
After this reform, the number of products subject to industrial product production license management will be reduced from last year's 38 categories to the current 24 categories.
The Decision makes it clear that simplified approval procedures shall be implemented for the products in the catalogue.
The first is to change the pre-licensing product inspection organized by the license-issuing authority to the product inspection qualification report issued by the qualified inspection and testing institution submitted by the enterprise when applying.
Second, in addition to dangerous chemicals, the product licensed by the quality and technical supervision department (market supervision and administration department) of the provincial people's government shall be subject to post-site inspection. After submitting the application and the product inspection qualification report and making a commitment to ensure the product quality and safety, the enterprise may obtain the production license after passing the formal examination, and then accept the on-site inspection within the prescribed time.
Thirdly, in accordance with the principle of "one enterprise, one license ", when applying for a new license or applying for a new license, a license certificate shall be examined and issued together.
The Decision requires that all regions and relevant departments should firmly promote the work of reducing the catalogue and simplifying the examination and approval procedures.
We will intensify the work of publicizing the commitments of enterprises and on-site review, strengthen the means of credit supervision and restraint, implement the responsibilities of enterprises as quality subjects, and revoke the production license for those who make false promises and do not meet the requirements.
For products that have been removed from the administration of production licenses for industrial products, it is necessary to effectively strengthen the supervision after the event. Products involving public health and safety, environmental protection and other products may be turned into mandatory certification. A positive list shall be drawn up and made public to the public. The certification standards shall be unified, and the certification and testing items shall be reasonably reduced. In principle, the mandatory certification fees shall be borne by the finance at all levels according to the system.
Support measures should be taken to encourage enterprises to carry out voluntary certification, promote brand building and expand the market.
We should benchmark international advanced standards and promote the quality improvement of industrial products.
give full play to the role of third-party social organizations and ensure the quality and safety of industrial products.
For products that retain the management of production licenses for industrial products, it is necessary to improve the standard system, give play to the advantages of industry supervision, strengthen the responsibility of "who approves and who supervises ", dynamically assess the risks of product quality and safety, timely reduce the catalogue, delegate the authority for examination and approval or turn to certification management.
In September, China's comprehensive PMI ring ratio increased the manufacturing PMI ring ratio fell.
According to the data released by the National Bureau of Statistics of China on the 30th, in September, China ’ s comprehensive PMI output index was 54.1%, higher than the previous month and the average annual value of 0.3 and 0.1 percentage points, indicating that the overall production and operation activities of Chinese enterprises remained stable.
During the month, the manufacturing production index and the non-manufacturing business activity index, which make up the composite PMI output index, were 53.0% and 54.9%, respectively, down one litre from the previous month.
Among them, China ’ s manufacturing PMI was 50.8%, down 0.5 percentage points month-on-month.
Zhao Qinghe said that this month's manufacturing PMI has five main characteristics:
First, the fundamentals of manufacturing industry are generally stable.
Of the 21 industries surveyed, the PMI of 14 industries is in the expansion range. Among them, the PMI of pharmaceutical, special equipment, electrical machinery equipment and other manufacturing industries is at a high operating level above 53.5%, with a fast growth rate.
The second is the small fluctuation of supply and demand.
The production index and the new order index were 53.0% and 52.0%, respectively, down 0.3 and 0.2 percentage points from the previous month. Supply and demand continued to remain buoyant, but the expansion slowed slightly.
The new export order index and import index were 48.0% and 48.5%, respectively, down from 1.4% and 0.6 percentage points in the previous month. The business climate fell to year lows.
Fourth, the cost of purchasing raw materials for enterprises has increased.
The purchasing price index of major raw materials was 59.8%, 1.1 percentage points higher than that of the previous month. The ex-factory price index was 54.3%, the same as that of the previous month. Both were year highs.
Fifth, the operation of large enterprises is robust, and the operating conditions of small enterprises continue to improve.
The PMI of large enterprises was 52.1%, the same as that of the previous month. Since the beginning of this year, the index has always been in the expansion range of 52.0% and above, and both the production index and the new order index have increased month-on-month. This is the main driving force for the manufacturing sector to keep expanding. The PMI of medium-sized enterprises is 48.7%, down from 1.7 percentage points in the previous month, and is in the contraction range. The PMI of small enterprises is 50.4%, up from 0.4 percentage points in the previous month, rising for two consecutive months.
In the same month, China ’ s non-manufacturing business activity index stood at 54.9%, up 0.7 percentage points from the previous month, and rebounded for two consecutive months.
Zhao Qinghe believes that the non-manufacturing industry as a whole continues to maintain a steady and positive momentum of development.
The business activity index of road transport, securities, real estate and other industries continues to be below the critical point, and the total business volume has decreased.
Nagoya, Nov 5 (Reuters) - Bank of Japan President Haruhiko Kuroda said on Monday that the central bank is aware that the long-term implementation of ultra-loose monetary policy could squeeze the profit margins of financial institutions and could destabilize the country's banking system.
But he said that given low inflation and uncertainty in overseas economies, the Bank of Japan needs to maintain its massive stimulus program while keeping a close eye on the pros and cons of its policies.
"The Bank of Japan fully recognizes that under continued monetary easing, the strength of financial institutions will be increasingly affected," Kuroda said in a speech to business leaders in Nagoya.
He said that if financial institutions were more active in taking risks to compensate for the narrowing of profit margins caused by years of low interest rates, there could be turbulence in the banking system in the event of a serious negative shock.
"Although these risks are not significant at present, the central bank will closely monitor the development of the situation and encourage financial institutions to take necessary measures," he said.
Minutes of the Bank of Japan meeting released earlier on Monday showed that at the September meeting, the policy committee of the Bank of Japan discussed the rising cost of long-term easing.
According to the minutes of the meeting, one member said that if the economy continues to expand, "the Bank of Japan will have more room for flexibility in policy in the future."
The minutes of the meeting showed that another member said that given the limitations of the duration of the policy, the committee should discuss how long the Bank of Japan can maintain the stimulus policy.
Kuroda said the Bank of Japan will assess the financial risks posed by the easing policy, while also taking into account the uncertainty surrounding Japan's economic outlook, which may affect global demand due to Sino-U.S. trade frictions and rising protectionism.
"The impact of such issues on the Japanese economy is temporarily limited," Kuroda said.
"But how the problem continues, the impact on Japan's economy is likely to become greater," he added.
"There is a need for continued strong monetary easing, while considering both positive and negative effects in a balanced manner," Kuroda said.
While the downsides of the aggressive stimulus program have increased, such as long-term low interest rates that have eroded the profits of financial institutions, low inflation has forced the Bank of Japan to maintain the program.
The Bank of Japan maintained monetary policy last month; in the face of the risks posed by the end of the global trade war, Kuroda ruled out raising interest rates in the near future.
