The death toll from Indonesia's strong earthquake and tsunami rose to 420. There were no reports of casualties among Chinese citizens
The death toll from the powerful earthquake and tsunami in Indonesia's Central Sulawesi province has risen to 420, the official Antara news agency said at midnight local time, citing figures released by Wilem Rampangilei, the head of the country's disaster relief agency.
According to the official, this is only the statistics of the city of Palu, the capital of Central Sulawesi Province. It does not include Dungara County, where the epicenter is located, and the nearby Sigi area, as communication between the two areas is still suspended and no number of victims have been reported.
Because many roads in the city of Palu have been severely damaged, heavy machinery is difficult to access, and search and rescue efforts have encountered great difficulties.
In order to safeguard the rescue, the Palu airport, which began to close on the night of the 28th, suspended all commercial flights after reopening on the night of the 29th. The flight from Jakarta to Palu was cancelled after the reporter had completed the boarding pass that night.
After the earthquake and tsunami occurred, the Chinese Embassy in Indonesia immediately learned and verified the situation of Chinese citizens in the disaster area through various channels.
Up to now, there have been no reports of casualties among Chinese citizens.
