TOKYO, Oct 1 (Reuters) - Confidence among Japan's big manufacturers hit its lowest level in more than a year in the September quarter, according to the Bank of Japan's short-term survey quarterly report released on Monday, as rising raw material costs and a series of natural disasters affected production, putting pressure on companies.
The survey showed little evidence that escalating global trade frictions have dampened the confidence of large manufacturers.
But the risk of a full-blown trade war has hit the business outlook of companies and could threaten their capital spending.
Active capital spending is a bright spot in Japan's economy.
The survey calls into question the Bank of Japan's view that a robust economic expansion will help accelerate inflation to the 2% target, despite signs that companies are gradually shifting costs to customers.
"Amid fears of a global trade war, the confidence of manufacturers tends to stagnate due to slowing exports and weak factory production," said Nan Wuzhi, chief researcher at the Institute of Agroforestry.
"Confidence is still high. And because corporate profits are improving and prices are rising, I don't think confidence will continue to decline."
A short-term survey showed that the large-scale manufacturing business sentiment judgment index fell to positive 19 in September from positive 21 three months ago, marking the third consecutive quarter of deterioration.
The market's median estimate is positive 22.
The large non-manufacturing business sentiment index fell to positive 22 in September from positive 24 in the June survey, the first deterioration in eight quarters.
The Reuters survey was positive 22.
The survey showed that both the large-scale manufacturing and non-manufacturing business sentiment indicators were expected to remain stable in December.
Investors did not care about the decline of the short-term business sentiment judgment index. The Japanese Nikkei .N225 rose to a 27-year high on Monday, as the continued depreciation of the yen helped improve the export earnings prospects of Japanese companies.
Capital expenditure is sound.
Despite the decline in business confidence, the latest short-term outlook highlights the robustness of corporate capital spending plans, thanks to the renewal of capacity and increased investment in robotics and automation to cope with the labor shortage caused by an aging population.
According to a short-term survey by the central bank, large enterprises plan to increase their capital expenditure by 13.4% in the current fiscal year ending March 2019.
At the time of the previous short view survey, it was 13.6%.
Nanwuzhi said that the capital expenditure plan of all enterprises grew by 8.5% in the current fiscal year, close to the pace of Japan ’ s bubble economy era.
"There is still room for further growth in capital spending, given that small businesses have raised their profit estimates from now on, but much depends on the impact of the trade war on business confidence," he said.
The short-term survey shows that the ability of enterprises to pass on costs has increased. The output price index of large enterprises is positive 7, which is a ten-year high. This is an encouraging sign, reflecting the progress of Japan's efforts to fight deflation.
The index measuring the employment status of large enterprises hit minus 23, the tightest level since 1992, highlighting the tightening of the employment market.
Thanks to robust corporate spending, Japan's economy rebounded in the second quarter from a contraction in January-March this year.
But the escalation of trade frictions in the summer and the disruption of the supply chain by natural disasters have clouded the prospects of the export-dependent Japanese economy.
