The 69th International Astronautical Congress opened in Germany - CNN
Xinhua News Agency, Bremen, Germany, October 1 (reporter Ren Ke Zhang Yirong) The 69th International Astronautical Congress kicked off on October 1 at the Bremen Convention and Exhibition Center in Germany. More than 6,300 astronauts, representatives of space agencies and enterprises, experts, scholars and young students from all over the world attended.
In a speech delivered at the opening ceremony, the President of the International Astronautical Federation, Jean-Yves Legar, said that the global space industry is no longer attended by only a few countries and institutions. This year, the number of participants has increased significantly over the previous session, indicating that more and more institutions and people are joining in.
He called on all countries to strengthen cooperation and innovation and jointly promote the development of the space industry.
Zhang Kejian, Vice Minister of China's Ministry of Industry and Information Technology and Director-General of the National Space Administration, introduced China's space program at the exchange event and said that China will expand international cooperation in the space field and make contributions to the space industry of mankind.
Representatives of China Aerospace Science and Technology Corporation, China Aerospace Science and Technology Corporation and other relevant institutions, as well as some private enterprises, attended the meeting and showcased the latest achievements of China's spaceflight, including various launch vehicles, satellites and space science and technology application products.
The International Astronautical Congress, which has been held annually since 1950, is the biggest event in the world aviation community.
The five-day conference was jointly hosted by the International Astronautical Federation, the International Academy of Astronautics, the Centre for Applied Science and Technology and Microgravity Research of the University of Bremen, and the International Institute of Space Law.
BEIJING, Nov 5 (Reuters) - A press release issued by the China Foreign Trade Center on Sunday said that the Canton Trade Fair showed that China's foreign trade situation remains complex and grim, with 80.6 percent of enterprises predicting that the export situation for the whole of 2018 is better than that of the previous year or flat.
However, taking into account the external environment in which the cost of domestic raw materials, labor and other comprehensive factors continues to rise and the impact of trade friction between China and the United States has increased, the participating enterprises also believe that the export situation next year is not optimistic.
At the closing press conference of the 124th Canton Trade Fair, Xu Bing, deputy secretary-general of the Canton Trade Fair, press spokesman and deputy director of the China Foreign Trade Center, said that the number of overseas buyers and export transactions of the current Canton Trade Fair had declined slightly year-on-year.
The number of buyers attending the meeting was 189,812, from 215 countries and regions, down 1.11% year on year.
Export transactions amounted to RMB206.494 billion (equivalent to US $29.86 billion), a year-on-year decline of 1%.
From the market point of view, transactions with Japan, the ten ASEAN countries, the BRIC countries and South Korea increased by 74.4%, 11.4%, 7.2% and 2.5%, respectively, while the traditional markets such as the United States, Australia, Canada and the European Union fell by 30.3%, 8.9%, 7.3% and 0.8%, respectively.
In terms of industry, means of transport, machinery and equipment, construction and decoration materials, electronic consumer goods and information products, and sanitary equipment increased by 24.8%, 21.1%, 20.0%, 15.1%, and 7.6%, respectively. Textile clothing and household appliances fell by 13.0% and 6.7%, respectively.
Xu Bing said that, as a barometer and weather vane of China's foreign trade, the situation of the buyers participating in the current Canton Trade Fair and the export transaction data show that China's foreign trade development will still face many uncertain and unstable factors next year.
However, with the in-depth promotion of supply-side structural reform and the recent introduction of policies and measures in the areas of "six stability" by the state and local governments, the new dynamic energy of China's foreign trade development is accelerating and new progress has been made in the diversification of the enterprise market. These are important foundations and powerful conditions for the development of foreign trade.
"Taking all factors into account, it is expected that China's foreign trade imports and exports will maintain a steady growth throughout the year, with further improvement in quality and efficiency," Xu Bing said.
The General Administration of Customs of China announced that exports in US dollar terms rose by 14.5% year-on-year in September, while imports grew by 14.3% year-on-year. The trade surplus in September was US $31.69 billion. The export growth rate and trade surplus in September were the highest since February this year.
Despite the escalating trade friction between China and the United States, China's export performance in September was still significantly higher than expected. The strong external demand, the rush of enterprises to export before the imposition of tariffs by the United States and the depreciation of the RMB exchange rate, or the main supporting factors, also showed the resilience of China's foreign trade. However, the impact of the trade war between China and the United States on confidence and the impact on the industrial chain cannot be underestimated. Analysts believe that the challenges of China's foreign trade may become apparent in the fourth quarter or next year.
According to a Reuters survey, U.S. fund managers recommended increasing their cash holdings in September, maintaining a cautious stance as the United States and China began the latest round of reciprocal import tariffs and the dispute showed no signs of easing.
But according to the 12 fund managers involved in the survey, North America's asset allocation rose to its highest since June 2017, while the UK, the eurozone and especially emerging markets saw their positions fall.
The share of global stock allocation averaged 56.6%, while the share of bonds was 35.5%, basically in line with last month ’ s survey.
Its most obvious change is that the cash ratio rose to 5.1%, the highest since December 2014.
"Some economic data have brought confidence to the market, but the trade war is still the biggest concern, so it's best to be prepared to enter when the market falls back," said a fund manager at a large fund company.
But fund managers still preferred stocks in September, especially U.S. stocks, even though U.S. stocks were considered to be overpriced.
