Foreign media: The U.S. and Canada reached a framework agreement on the North American Free Trade Agreement.
[Abstract] The agreement includes Canada opening up its dairy market to the United States, and the United States temporarily not imposing tariffs on Canadian-made cars.
According to foreign media, a Canadian source revealed on the night of September 30, local time, that the United States and Canada have reached a framework agreement on the North American Free Trade Agreement.
It was revealed that the agreement included Canada opening up its dairy market to the United States, and the United States temporarily not imposing tariffs on Canadian-made cars.
On the 27th of last month, the United States and Mexico announced that they had reached a preliminary agreement in principle on updating the North American Free Trade Agreement. However, the United States and Canada failed to reach an agreement before the August 31 deadline set by the United States to extend the negotiation period to September 30.
Earlier, a spokesman for Canadian Foreign Minister Freeland said that Canada would only sign a favorable agreement, "focusing on the substance, not the timetable. We will continue to consult and hope to reach an agreement that is in Canada's national interest."
More than 90% of Brazilian women voters said the presidential candidate did not take into account the needs of women.
According to data released recently by the National Geographic Institute of Brazil (IBGE), more than 90% of Brazilian women do not believe that presidential candidates take into account the needs of women, according to the South American Overseas Chinese News Network.
According to the report, the number of women in Brazil has reached 107 million. If all Brazilian women are brought together to form a country, the country's population will rank 13th in the world, more than twice that of Spain's entire population.
In Brazil, the number of female voters accounts for 52% of the total number of voters, with men accounting for 48%. Although the proportion of women in the electorate is very high, in the Brazilian Congress, women account for only 10%.
Among the world's 193 countries, Brazilian women's participation in politics is ranked only 154th, higher than that of Arab countries.
After more than 20 years of struggle for rights, Brazilian women still haven't succeeded in obtaining their due rights.
Natalia Mori, a Brazilian sociologist, pointed out that the reason for this phenomenon lies in the combination of ancient patrilineal society, racism, and capitalist values.
"Politics is supposed to consist of citizens claiming civil rights, identity, access to public goods and the formation of the same society by multiple social groups. But Brazilian politics is the monopoly of one group, and most of the population is not represented."
A previous study conducted by Locomotiva also pointed out that 94% of Brazilian women do not feel that elected politicians can represent their rights, 90% of Brazilian women do not agree with the decisions made by politicians, and 93% do not agree with the current government policy.
"We need to reverse the underrepresentation of women in parliament. Brazil's political system is still affected by inequality. So far, there is still serious gender, class and racial discrimination in Brazil's political sphere," said Natalia Mori.
Despite the lack of women's rights, most Brazilian women still believe in the power of democracy.
The survey showed that 76% of women think they can make a difference in democratic elections, and 72% are interested in politics.
In addition, 55% of women believe that democratic politics is the best way to subject women to less prejudice.
