The T2 terminal of Guangxi Guilin Liangjiang International Airport was officially opened on the 30th.
Zhao Leqin, secretary of the CPC Guilin Municipal Committee, said that after the opening of the new terminal, it can meet the annual passenger throughput demand of 12 million passengers, and build a new advantage in Guilin air traffic. It is of great significance to further improve the modern three-dimensional transportation pattern of the "four-in-one" of Guangxi's river-sea linkage, sea-rail connection, land-and-sea connection and air-port connection.
This year Guilin is expected to receive more than 90 million visitors.
The expansion project of the T2 terminal and the supporting facilities of the station at Guilin Liangjiang International Airport is a major public welfare project for the 60th anniversary of the founding of Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region. It is also a landmark project for the construction of Guilin international tourist resorts.
The project started in December 2015, with a construction area of 100,000 square meters and a total investment of RMB3.258 billion. Upon completion and commissioning, the project will meet the needs of 12 million annual passenger throughput, 10.12 million flights and 95,000 tons of cargo and postal throughput.
On the same day, more than 200 flights took off and landed at the T2 terminal of Guilin Liangjiang International Airport.
The design of the new terminal building is inspired by the mountains and waters of Guilin. It looks like a "mountain and water crown" from afar. It looks like the "dragon ridge terraces" and the tiered eaves of the folk houses of northern Guangxi. It is in harmony with the mountains and waters of Guilin.
According to the report, the new terminal of Guilin Airport can meet the peak flow of nearly 4,000 arrivals and departures per hour. It has applied intelligent baggage sorting system, security integration platform, face recognition and other "smart airport" technical means, and has planned a business district that covers a wide range of industries, including catering, department stores, tax exemption and leisure and entertainment.
