On September 29, China's first 3,000-ton large-scale buoy ship, the "Xiangyanghong 22 ", was launched at the China Wushu Group.
When completed, the ship will break the current equipment bottleneck of China in the safeguard work of large-scale buoys, submersible marking, recovery, and emergency repair.
The "Xiangyanghong 22" wheel is mainly used for the regular inspection and maintenance of buoys/submersibles, the regular deployment and recovery of buoys/submersibles, the emergency deployment, recovery and repair of buoys/submersibles, as well as the ability to carry out comprehensive marine investigation tasks such as cross-sectional investigation.
The new ship is 89 meters in length, 18 meters in width, 7.2 meters in depth, and has a capacity of 10,000 nautical miles.
Wang Weiling, deputy general manager of the Wushu Group, said: "Xiangyanghong 22 is the first large-scale buoy operation ship in China, and the only working ship in China with the operational capability of lifting ten-meter large buoys. It will further enhance China's large-scale buoy security capability."
