Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) is a chronic and difficult disease involving multiple organs throughout the body. It has been considered an "incurable disease" in the past.
Because its pathogenesis is not clear, diagnosis and treatment are difficult, and there is no effective treatment method.
Recently, Liu Wanli, a researcher at Tsinghua University ’ s School of Life Sciences, and Li Zhanguo, director of the Rheumatism Immunology Center of Peking University ’ s People ’ s Hospital, discovered that human immunoglobulin has a molecular mutation that increases susceptibility to systemic lupus erythematosus, and that this variation is involved in regulating immune B cells.
In short, the two teams confirmed that an abnormal immune molecule in the body is an important cause of the onset of systemic lupus erythematosus.
According to one of the authors of the article, Sun Xiaolin of Peking University People's Hospital, the Li Zhanguo team collected nearly 2,000 cases of systemic lupus erythematosus patients with large samples and conducted research. It was found that the patients with immunoglobulin variation produced a wide variety of disease-causing cells and a large number of autoantibodies. The incidence and severity of inflammation such as nephritis, arthritis, serous inflammation and vasculitis significantly increased.
Liu Wanli's team discovered the immune signaling pathway activated by the mutation of the immune molecule and the pathogenic mechanism of promoting the secretion of multiple autoantibodies by B cells through various research methods such as immune cell tracing, animal testing, sequencing and so on.
Reporters learned that the two teams worked together to give full play to their respective advantages, and achieved a close combination of basic research and clinical application.
Liu Wanli's team is committed to the study of B-lymphocyte immune recognition and immune activation, while Li Zhanguo's team has long been engaged in the clinical study of systemic lupus erythematosus.
"This study is one of the results of many years of cooperation between the two teams. It is also the first time that the academic community has recognized that the abnormal immunoglobulin gene will induce systemic lupus erythematosus. It has laid a solid foundation for further academic research and clinical targeted treatment."
