A three-way trade agreement between the United States, Canada and Mexico will bring new opportunities for 500 million people.
According to foreign media reports, the joint statement of Canadian Foreign Minister Freeland and U.S. Trade Representative Lighthizer, published on the Canadian government website, said that the United States, Canada and Mexico reached a three-way trade agreement, which will be known as the "USMCA" (US-Mexico-Canada Agreement).
Earlier, Canada's CTV News television quoted senior U.S. sources as saying that Canada and the United States had resolved their differences and reached an agreement on the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA).
The Washington Post, citing two sources with knowledge of the situation, reported that the agreement reached between the United States and Canada on September 30 will retain the North American Free Trade Agreement as a three-party trade agreement, and the heads of the three countries will sign a new agreement within two months.
"Today, Canada, the United States and Mexico have agreed on a new trade agreement - the USMCA, which will provide a high standard of trade agreement for our workers, farmers and companies. It will lead to freer markets, fairer trading and more sustainable economic growth. The agreement will strengthen the middle class, create high-paying jobs and create new opportunities for about 500 million people," the statement said.
It is reported that the current North American Free Trade Agreement was signed by the United States, Mexico and Canada in 1994.
After his inauguration as president, Trump announced plans to revisit the agreement and sign a new deal.
The three countries began this negotiation process in 2017.
The results of the Okinawa governor's election, which was held ahead of schedule due to the illness and death of former Governor Ong Xiongzhi, were announced in the early hours of the morning local time. Yucheng Danny, who opposed the planned relocation of the US military base in Japan, was successfully elected.
The election was held on September 30. The final result showed that Yucheng received a total of 3966.32 million votes, the highest number of votes in the history of the Okinawa governor's election, and more than 80,000 more votes than his main election opponent, Saki Shinsoon.
A total of four candidates participated in the election, with a turnout of 63.24%, down 0.89 percentage points from the 2014 election of governor of Okinawa Prefecture.
Yucheng told the media on Monday that the election results showed that the county people did not want to let the efforts of Governor Weng before his death be in vain. He will carry on the legacy of Governor Weng and continue to make efforts to the Japanese government and the US government on opposing the relocation plan of the US military base and the closure of the Futenma base.
The U.S. military base of Futenma, located in Yiyewan City, Okinawa Prefecture, has long been criticized. The Japanese and U.S. government had previously agreed to relocate it to the border area of the famous city, but the people of Okinawa strongly opposed it, hoping to move the base out of Okinawa completely.
As for the relocation plan strongly opposed by the county residents and the requirement to revoke the land reclamation permit along the ancient coast of Bianye, Yucheng said that he did not stand in opposition and split with the central government at the beginning. He hoped that the two sides could fully exchange views and showed their intention to resolve the issue through consultation.
Japanese Prime Minister Abe Jinsan also told the media on the morning of the first day of the month that he seriously accepted the result and would make efforts to revitalize Okinawa and reduce the burden of the base.
At a press conference on Monday, Japan's Chief Secretary of State Yoshihide Suga said that there has been no change in the government's policy on moving US military bases as soon as possible.
At the same time, he also expressed his intention to talk with Yucheng.
Yucheng will be officially installed as governor of Okinawa Prefecture on the 4th of this month.
Since the mid-2000s, as China's demand for oilseeds has grown, Paul Thomas, a farmer in North Dakota, has grown more and more soybeans in his fields.
The shift culminated this year, when he planted 1,600 acres of soybeans in 5,000 acres, on a scale never seen before.
But Thomas and many farmers like him plan to switch to the staple crops of the former U.S. agricultural region in 2019: corn and wheat.
U.S. farmers planted more soybeans than corn this year, for the first time in 35 years.
The reason for the plan to switch to other food crops is that U.S. farmers face difficulties selling soybeans against the backdrop of President Donald Trump's trade war against China.
China typically buys about 60% of U.S. exports of soybeans, but the trade war has resulted in almost zero purchases of U.S. soybeans in recent months, causing soybean prices to fall to decade lows.
Thomas intends to grow more wheat next year, hoping to make more money by reducing its dependence on crops that depend on Chinese demand.
Thomas said the price of soybeans "has hit us hard."
Without Chinese demand, he said, the spot price of soybeans near his farm is $7.10 per bushel, while the price necessary to cover the cost is $8.50.
U.S. farmers planted a record amount of soybeans this year, and the harvest is expected to reach a record high.
At such a vulnerable moment, they were hit by a trade war.
In response to Trump's imposition of tariffs on imports of Chinese goods, China imposed import tariffs on imports of American soybeans in July.
The U.S. Department of Agriculture will release its first estimate of next year's planting area, which is expected to include consideration of the impact of tariffs.
It is expected that the estimate will confirm the expectation of the private sector that soybean seeding area will be reduced.
According to a report seen by Reuters, Informa Economics predicted on October 19 that corn acreage will increase by 4% to 92.7 million acres (37.5 million hectares) in 2019, while soybean acreage will be reduced by 7% to 83 million acres.
Informa also expects a 4% increase in wheat acreage in the US.
Soybean acreage planted before the retaliatory tariffs rose to 89.6 million acres this year, some 15 million acres higher than 10 years ago.
Corn acreage has increased by less than 5 million acres since 2008 to 89.1 million acres, and wheat acreage is 47.8 million acres this year, near the lowest level in 100 years.
Aron Carlson, president of the Illinois Corn Growers Association, has a total planting area of 3,600 acres. This year, he spent nearly half of it on soybeans, but plans to cut back in the future.
He said it was possible to increase corn acreage by up to 20% at his farm in northern Illinois, the largest soybean-growing state in the country.
Soybean yield per acre is lower than that of corn, but it also requires less fertilizer, which makes it cheaper to grow soybeans overall.
If farmers switch to final-value corn, it may raise costs, but it will benefit some businesses, including Andersons Inc. fertilizer sellers.
Andersons CEO Pat Bowe told Reuters he expects the switch to corn will benefit fertilizer use.
Bayer is also expected to benefit from farmers switching to maize.
