In recent years, there have been incidents of unqualified plastic runways on campus in many places.
To this end, the Ministry of Education issued a notice that the new national standard must be implemented for the surface sports venues of synthetic materials for primary and secondary schools to be delivered for use after November 1 this year.
The compulsory national standard 鈥淪ynthesis Materials Surface Sports Grounds for Primary and Secondary Schools鈥? was led by the Ministry of Education and drafted with the participation of 26 scientific research institutes and testing institutions. After more than two years of revision, more than 100 expert meetings were organized during the period, as well as on-the-spot inspection and sample inspection throughout the country, and numerous verification experiments of products of hundreds of enterprises on the market were collected.
In comparison with the old national standard of 2005, reporters found that the new national standard has not only changed from a "national recommended standard" to a "national mandatory standard ", but also added a number of contents, including thickness requirements, physical properties, anti-aging properties, inorganic filler content requirements, anti-slip adhesive high polymer content requirements, limit of harmful substances in finished products, limit of harmful substances in non-solid and solid raw materials.
In particular, it is worth mentioning that the new national standard has set a limit on the harmful substances that may be produced in the construction of plastic runways on campus, from the original 7 items to 18 items, and has set a limit on the amount of volatile organics in the runways after construction in accordance with the home improvement standards.
For example, the release of hazardous substances is specified in the "Limits and odour requirements of hazardous substances in cast-in-place and prefabricated surface products ". Total volatile organic compounds are required to be no higher than 5 mg/m3, formaldehyde no higher than 0.4 mg/m3, carbon disulfide no higher than 7 mg/m3, benzene no higher than 0.1 mg/m3, and odour grade no higher than 3.
The new national standard has also made detailed provisions on the sampling requirements, inspection rules, judging rules and other issues of plastic runways in primary and secondary schools.
In addition, the campus artificial lawn has also been included in the compulsory testing scope of the national standard for the first time.
In the near future, all localities should carry out special work arrangements on the implementation of the new national standard, and submit the implementation of the new national standard to the Department of Physical Education, Health and Arts Education of the Ministry of Education within the year.
